the reactor on japans only nuclear ship has been 
started for the first time since it was shut down 16 years ago due 
to a radiation leak 
no leakage of radiation was recorded during thursdays 12hour 
test aboard the 8242ton mutsu anchored at sekinehama in northern 
japan officials of the governments atomic energy reserach 
institute said 
the freighter developed a leak in its radioactive shield on its 
maiden voyage in 1974 and drifted for 50 days before city 
residents allowed it to return temporarily several other cities 
refused to berth the stricken vessel 
in 1981 government officials agreed to build a new port for the 
ship at sekinehama an isolated spot on the pacific ocean near its 
former home port mutsu city 
the ships reactor was extensively remodeled after the leak 
the officials said the tests of the reactor would continue and 
if successful the mutsu will conduct several test cruises to 
collect data for possible future development of nuclearpowered 
commercial vessels it then will be scrapped they said 
