<TEXT>
the soviet union may follow the lead of 
neighboring poland and begin a shock therapy plan to push the 
economy toward a market system a senior official says 
but vyacheslav senchagov chief of the state price committee 
also told deputies of the supreme soviet legislature that angry 
consumers could block such radical economic changes 
the government favors a moderate approach toward a market system 
that includes a transition period he said thursday in remarks 
carried by the official tass news agency 
however tass said senchagov acknowledged choosing the most 
radical approach is inevitable if during the transitional period 
the populations confidence in the government does not fall so 
low as to make no reforms possible 
the most radical of three alternatives being considered is 
likely to drastically raise prices for raw materials and consumer 
goods reduce the value of the ruble and raise unemployment he was 
quoted as saying 
senchagov said the government has not yet decided which approach 
it will try to put into effect 
after being installed in a powerful presidency on march 15 
mikhail s gorbachev said his most important task was to take more 
radical steps to cure the economy 
last week a source confirmed previous news reports that 
gorbachevs economists are working on a 17point program leading to 
a market system and convertibility of the soviet unions currency 
on world markets 
the source who is working on the program said soviet 
economists were encouraged by polands tough measures that went 
into effect on jan 1 but they were worried they might create huge 
unemployment and the need for a vast welfare program the source 
spoke on condition of anonymity 
many reports in moscow say radical economic changes will be put 
into effect this summer 
senchagovs bureaucracy sets prices without regard to costs 
creating artificially low prices for oil and gas and many natural 
resources as well as for food and basic consumer goods 
but the artificially low return for soviet industry stifles 
production and initiative 
subsidies to keep prices low now cost the government the 
equivalent of onefifth the total volume of the countrys retail 
trade senchagov reported 
consumers have become used to a system that offers a minimum of 
choice for low prices and many react with alarm to reports that 
the government is planning to free prices public concern has 
forced the government to delay key price reforms several times 
as a result of government management of prices one 
videocassette costs about twice as much as a 1200mile airline 
trip 
also the country has long told its people they have a right to 
a job but many enterprises lose money because of bloated payrolls 
polands prices have increased 1366 percent during the 12month 
period ending feb 28 the warsaw government says and more than 
200000 people are unemployed but under polands drastic economic 
plan inflation has dropped from 79 percent in january to an 
estimated 6 percent in march 
poland has restocked its store shelves while soviets see their 
stores becoming emptier and emptier 
the most conservative of the three approaches in moscow would 
raise some prices for raw materials and some manufactured goods by 
fixed amounts 
under the most radical approach however oil and coal prices 
will increase three to five times the number of collective and 
state farms known for their inefficiency will drop by 80 percent 
unprofitable enterprises will be closed and unemployment will 
increase fast tass quoted senchagov as saying 
</TEXT>
