widespread said simpson who has played a major role in writing 
immigration laws 
the law designed to curb the flow of illegals over the southern 
border in search of highpaying jobs calls for civil and criminal 
penalties against those who employ ineligible workers 
critics predicted when the measure was passed by congress in 
1986 that it would cause employers to discriminate against 
foreignlooking applicants 
the gaos report said the law is not an unnecessary burden on 
employers it concluded that the measure has not caused frivolous 
complaints against employers and has apparently reduced illegal 
immigration 
ins figures show that 383375 illegals were apprehended on the 
southern border from october 1987 through february 1988 compared 
with 267174 in the same period a year later in the comparable 
period ending last month apprehensions increased to 366844 
the ins mcnary told a news conference the number of 
apprehensions would have doubled had it not been for the 1986 
immigration law and the gao report cited a study by the urban 
institute that found a slowing of illegal immigration 
the gao said many employers discriminated because the laws 
verification system does not provide a simple or reliable method to 
verify job applicants eligibility to work 
it said up to 10 percent of the 46 million employers considered 
under the gao survey may be practicing job bias based on national 
origins because of confusion over the immigration law 
discrimination related to the law is serious but not 
pervasive the 162page report said it said hiring bias might be 
reduced by more information for employers and a simpler and more 
reliable system for verifying work eligibility 
under the law employers must complete an eligibility form for 
each newly hired worker it allows the employees to establish their 
eligibility by presenting any one of 17 documents such as a us 
passport birth certificate or alien registration card 
in response to the report the us commission on civil rights 
urged congress to repeal the laws penalty provisions saying 
evidence has been building rapidly in recent months that employer 
sanctions cause serious employment discrimination 
this discrimination is unacceptable and its root cause 
employer sanctions should be eliminated the independent 
factfinding agency said in a statement 
the ins mcnary told reporters that some of the gaos 
conclusions were soft because there is no base of comparison in 
the past he also pointed to a statement in the document that 
said some interpreters might not agree with the findings 
they own up to the fact that others may disagree and for good 
reason he said 
