<TEXT>
a recent sampling of moscow residents shows more 
than half of them could be mobilized by antisemites the american 
jewish committee says 
committee president sholom d comay told reporters thursday the 
survey indicates a significant part of the soviet population openly 
dislikes jews holds negative stereotypes about them or is at 
best neutral about jews and thus open to manipulation 
the sampling of 509 adults during february and march found 18 
percent indicated they disliked jews 65 percent indicated they 
were neutral and 18 percent indicated they liked jews 
the 65 percent who were neutral about jews are open to 
manipulation by enemies of jews and likely can be mobilized by 
antisemites committee research director david singer said 
history teaches that jews are secure only when people have 
genuinely positive feelings toward them he said it is not 
enough that people be nonantisemitic 
the committee called on president mikhail gorbachev and the 
soviet leadership to condemn manifestations of antisemitism 
of those surveyed 91 percent said jews should be free to 
decide for themselves whether they want to remain in the soviet 
union or emigrate 
and 90 percent agreed that the government should make every 
effort to see that the rights of jews to equal educational 
opportunities are respected and 88 percent favored equal 
employment opportunities for jews 
the study was conducted under the auspices of the institute of 
sociology of the soviet academy of sciences and directed by 
political scientists james gibson and raymond duch of the 
university of houston 
the study funded by the committee the national science 
foundation and the university of houston involved questions on 350 
items it has a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage 
points 
other findings included 
thirtythree percent maintained that when it comes to 
choosing between people and money jews will choose money 
twentynine percent were uncertain and 38 percent disagreed 
twentythree percent agreed that jews have too much influence 
over russian culture while 21 percent were uncertain and 56 
percent disagreed 
