chancellor helmut kohl of west germany today said 
a treaty confirming polands current borders should coincide with 
acknowledgment by poland that it mistreated germans who came under 
its rule after world war ii 
kohl was asked at a news conference to amplify on a speech he 
made to an anglogerman group in cambridge thursday night in which 
he urged poland to follow czechoslovakias example and recognize 
the injustice of expelling millions of germans 
in his reply kohl suggested that such a declaration should be 
made when a unified germany signs a treaty enshrining the existing 
oderneisse line as the legal and final germanpolish border 
there is the question of recognition of the oderneisse 
border to anchor it in a treaty of a unified germany with 
poland he said that is a historic moment and i think it is 
very good thing if at such a moment one can actually find a word of 
reconciliation 
he reiterated that he was not demanding an apology he did not 
specify whether such a declaration should be oral or in the form of 
a document 
kohls comments were seen in west germany as a new effort to 
keep the german exiles and their offspring on his side in national 
elections dec 2 about 13 million germans were expelled from 
prewar german territories that now are part of poland and 
czechoslovakia 
in warsaw government spokeswoman malgorzata niezabitowska said 
today that nazi atrocities far outweighed those committed by poles 
after the war but she wanted to hear exactly what kohl said before 
commenting further 
she stressed at a news conference that poles have spoken 
repeatedly of reconciliation she referred to a historic 1965 
letter from polish bishops to west german church leaders which said 
the poles forgave and asked forgiveness 
we think we have made so many statements on this issue that 
its clear she said 
kohl recalled that czechoslovak president vaclav havel already 
has expressed remorse over the postwar expulsion of the germans 
from his country 
if between germans and poles we could find similar words and 
we could talk to each other like that then this is a real peace 
and this is what i hope for he said 
the german leader was clearly aware of the sensitivity of such 
remarks given nazi atrocities in poland during the war on 
thursday he departed from his prepared text to tone it down so as 
not to accuse poland directly of mistreating the germans 
in the speech he also stressed he was not making any demand for 
a polish apology just a recognition of the injustice that was 
also inflicted on innocent germans 
we germans are not entitled to such words and even less must 
we try to balance accounts in one way or another he said 
