<DOCNO> AP900330-0063 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
spinal injury patients treated with a new 
drug recovered significantly more function than untreated patients 
in a clinical trial a federal agency reported today 
the national institute of neurological disorders and stroke said 
that in a clinical trial of 487 patients with acute spinal cord 
injury those treated with the drug methylprednisolone within eight 
hours of the injury recovered more motor and sensory function than 
those treated with other drugs or with a placebo 
the study started in 1977 was conducted at 10 us medical 
centers 
the report said that 162 patients were treated with 
methylprednisolone another 154 patients received naloxone and 171 
patients received placebos 
motor and sensory functions were assessed on admission and again 
six weeks after treatment and finally six months after injury 
the report said patients received methylprednisolone showed 
significant improvement in both muscle function and pin and touch 
sensation at six weeks and six months after injury the 
announcement said 
the drug must be given within eight hours of injury to be 
effective the study said 
the announcement said that the dose of methylprednisolone is 
critical and the successful dose was 30 milligrams for each 
kilogram of patient weight followed by an infusion of 54 
milligrams per kilogram of weight per hour for 23 hours 
lower doses of the medication were found not to be effective 
about 10000 americans each year suffer spinal cord injury with 
paralysis and the direct cost to the federal government for medical 
treatment for these injuries exceeds 4 billion annually 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

