here are highlights of the child care bill 
passed by the house on thursday 
the package is estimated to cost 27 billion over a fiveyear 
phase in period 
most of the money 185 billion would expand the earned 
income tax credit which goes to lowincome working families 
it would expand the head start program for disadvantaged 
children to provide child care throughout the calender year during 
each work day 
it would provide money for states to give to local school 
districts to expand establish or operate childcare programs based 
in the schools 
it would provide 29 billion to increase the title xx social 
servies block grant program for use by the states in providing 
childcare services states would be required to offer lowincome 
families vouchers to pay for child care operated by religious 
groups 
it would provide additional money for states to improve the 
quality of child care and to encourage private businesses to 
establish childcare programs 
it would phase out the existing dependentcare tax credit for 
families earning 70000 to 90000 and eliminate it above that 
level it would make permanent the 3 percent telephone excise tax 
