<TEXT>
ten years ago this weekend graduate 
student aaron lansky rented a modest loft took out corporation 
papers and launched an ambitious mission rescuing yiddish 
literature from extinction 
everybodys best guess was that there were about 75000 
volumes still extant here we are a million books later and still 
going strong he said there was no way to have imagined how 
prolific jews were as writers and readers 
now the founder of the national yiddish book center is turning 
to the business of trying to disseminate the thousands of books 
written in the language spoken by eastern european jews for 
hundreds of years and nearly erased in the holocaust 
our first 10 years was devoted to collecting and distributing 
books now well branch out and begin doing a great more he 
said our premise is now weve collected all these books weve 
got to open them up and let the world know whats inside of them 
lansky 33 has moved the center to nearby amherst and 
established a warehouse about 10 miles away in holyoke to hold the 
thousands of books sent in including some that were rescued from 
trash bins or plucked from attics 
in december he traveled to the soviet unions baltic states 
responding to letters from jews who hoped president mikhail 
gorbachevs reforms would mean a return for yiddish 
it was a pretty grueling experience in many ways he said 
what we found was that yiddish was not widely spoken in russia 
proper there is really what amounts to 70 years of assimilation 
lansky hopes to work out a system of shipping books to stockholm 
and then taking them personally into the soviet union 
the international venture goes far beyond the hopes he had as a 
student of yiddish who wanted to collect fodder for his research 
collecting the books was a big undertaking for us weve 
collected almost 1 million volumes which no one would have thought 
possible surprisingly enough theyre still coming in lansky 
said 
the nonprofit center has a staff of about two dozen and runs 
educational and cultural programs including the yiddish library 
development program about 70 libraries are participating 
