<TEXT>
contempt of court charges were filed friday 
against the us department of energy and the operator of the 
fernald uranium processing plant for allegedly violating a cleanup 
agreement 
state attorney general anthony j celebrezze jr accused the 
federal government and westinghouse materials co of ohio inc of 
mishandling hazardous waste containers failing to properly analyze 
some 40000 drums of radioactive material and failing to develop a 
written inspection schedule westinghouse operates the fernald 
plant 
the performance since 1988 has not been all bad but its 
my experience that only after we hit them with a club that they 
start compliance celebrezze said 
under a december 1988 consent decree the plant must comply with 
state and federal hazardous waste laws and pollution standards 
celebrezze said the consent decree gave the state clear authority 
to regulate disposal and treatment of hazardous waste 
the decree did not cover radioactive waste he said 
celebrezze asked us district judge s arthur spiegel to force 
the government to make proper environmental reports use safe 
containers for hazardous waste and guarantee that waste water does 
not spill on the ground 
celebrezze also is seeking proper sampling of the hazardous 
waste 
the attorney general said the state would leave the amount of 
any possible fine up to spiegel 
celebrezze said westinghouse did not sign the consent decree but 
is subject to its terms because the energy department signed on 
behalf of all contractors including westinghouse 
there was no immediate response from the energy department or 
westinghouse 
the fernald plant 18 miles northwest of cincinnati began 
processing uranium in 1951 for use in nuclear reactors and weapons 
the contractor operating the 1050acre plant westinghouse 
materials corp of ohio suspended production last year to 
concentrate on cleanup efforts 
a lawsuit on behalf of 14000 people living or working within 
five miles of the plant led to an unprecedented 78 million 
settlement last summer by the doe the government made its first 
16 million payment on the settlement last month 
the reagan administration called for closing the plant by the 
mid1990s but the current administration hasnt endorsed the plan 
the cleanup cost has been estimated at 1 billion to 5 billion 
the federal government entered into an agreement with ohio that 
gives the state courtenforceable regulatory authority over the 
cleanup of hazardous wastes not including nuclear waste 
stored at the plant in waste pits two concrete silos and 
thousands of 55gallon drums are more than 500000 metric tons of 
radioactive wastes dating from current plant operations to the 
world war iiera manhattan project to develop the atomic bomb 
the energy department in 1985 admitted that the plant had 
released about 300000 pounds of uranium oxide dust into the 
atmosphere over the years through faulty exhaustfilter systems 
