<TEXT>
dozens of screens offering crystal clear 
largerthanlife images of rock concerts boxing matches and 
surreal animation greeted broadcasters as the industrys annual 
convention began friday one term was on nearly everyones lips 
hdtv 
high definition television commanded center stage at the 
advanced technology exhibit which launched the national 
association of broadcasters fiveday convention 
dozens of hdtv screens offering sharp images flashed beside 
displays of high definition lenses fiberoptic cameras and special 
effects gizmos aimed at changing the way tv is made and watched 
hdtv would give viewers a picture far sharper than current 
broadcast standards by more than doubling the number of lines that 
make up a tv image 
a major issue overhanging the exhibits is how the disparate 
technology can be standardized and sold in a way that wont make 
obsolete the millions of television sets now in use 
convention organizers say hdtv probably wont be available to 
us homes until at least the middle of this decade 
the issues are not so much what is technically possible 
said michael c rau the associations senior vice president for 
science and technology rather the issues are what kind of hdtv 
actually can be achieved what technologies and standards can be 
agreed upon what technologies have consensus 
displays at the convention suggest that technologically 
speaking a great deal is possible 
for example the towering pioneer cube system that greeted 
visitors friday with an ultrasharp broadcast of a rock concert 
made it clear that tv can look a lot better than what most people 
see in their homes 
cube used a bank of 12 40inch hdtv screens each one showing a 
part of the larger picture and together presenting an image that 
was remarkably clear for a largescreen display 
drawing a small crowd nearby was an exhibit by the broadcasting 
technology association of tokyo of ghost reducer equipment 
designed to eliminate the multiple images that have bothered 
viewers since televisions infancy 
the problem occurs when television signals are reflected off 
mountains tall buildings or other structures officials said the 
new technology eliminates the problem by adding an extra signal at 
the transmitter which is picked up by a device on the tv set and 
used to filter out the distorted signal 
the system was standardized in japan in 1989 and is used by more 
than 100 tv stations there 
several us companies are working on similar technology but 
reducers are not expected to be available here for several years 
its not yet a consumer product because the demand will not 
justify the investment or the cost said amihai miron video 
department head for philips laboratories in briarcliff manor ny 
one of the us companies that have developed ghost reducer 
prototypes 
miron said it would cost up to 1200 under current conditions 
to equip a television set to use the system 
hundreds of additional exhibitors and dozens of panels and 
workshops are scheduled when the general sessions of the 
convention expected to draw more than 50000 people begin 
saturday 
president bush is scheduled to address the gathering monday 
 
