mass grave of unknown victims entry forbidden said the 
sign posted after authorities unearthed dozens more remains on 
friday skeletal parts from 200 to 1000 people some of them 
children have been unearthed officials said 
they said that after more than four decades identification of 
the victims would be extremely difficult and that it would be 
better not to further disturb the remains 
oranienburg authorities have now decided to seal off the mass 
grave said heinz erdmann deputy oranienburg district leader 
the dead should rest in peace they will not be transplanted 
erdmann said 
the site will be turned into a memorial erdmann said 
the camp about 30 miles north of berlin is one of several nazi 
camps later used by the soviets to hold german prisoners 
east german soldiers digging in the wooded area near the site of 
a former camp uncovered the skeletal remains of dozens more people 
friday 
the remains including skulls and nearly intact skeletons 
turned brown apparently from the soil in the region after more than 
40 years under ground 
some of the skeletons apparently were stacked upon each other 
while others were found alone over an area of about 300 square 
yards in the schmachtenhagener woods outside the town 
few clothes or other belongings were found in the area but 
rusted and illegible militarytype dogtag identification 
chains were found among the skeletons soldiers working at the site 
said 
also found were empty shell casings 
the official news agency adn reported this week that officials 
ordered the excavation after a local resident said that in the 
years after 1945 he witnessed naked prisoners being driven to the 
site on trucks 
according to the adn report the prisoners were forced to dig 
their own graves before they were shot and buried they were 
piled on each other like sardines in the graves the report said 
adn said the local prosecutors office in oranienburg has 
recommended that a special government commission be set up to 
investigate the mass burial site 
last weekend east german officials reported that a mass grave 
had been uncovered at fuenfeichen near neubrandenburg another of a 
total of 11 nazi internment camps taken over by the soviets in what 
is now east germany 
the existence of the graves had long been suspected but little 
evidence had surfaced until recently after the old communist 
regime was toppled last fall 
but it was unclear from whether the remains were from the 
postwar soviet era the period of nazi rule or both 
a west german official said 65000 to 70000 german prisoners 
may have died at the postwar soviet camps 
during the nazi era 6 million jews and hundreds of thousands of 
gypsies poles and others were killed 
 
