<TEXT>
britains prince philip said friday 
population growth has created an environmental crisis that could be 
more devastating than any nuclear holocaust if unchecked 
in a speech at the united nations prince philip said the 
problem was caused by human scientific and technological genius 
that led to rampant population growth 
it seems to me that it is about time that these same people 
the leaders in thought in politics and in administration began to 
face the facts and started to make serious efforts to find ways of 
solving the crisis he said 
the fuse of the population bomb has already been ignited and 
the consequences of the explosion for the future of the world will 
be a great deal more devastating than any nuclear holocaust he 
said in the speech sponsored by the un population fund 
prince philip president of the worldwide fund for nature said 
the ecological problems resulting from population growth are 
compounded because the countries facing the most dire circumstances 
are generally the poorest 
the prince recommended more international support for aid 
agencies so they can stabilize world population and avert 
conditions threatening many plant and animal species 
the un population fund estimates the current world population 
is nearly 53 billion people but it projects the figure will be 14 
billion by the year 2100 
prince philip said that while increasing numbers of people is 
the main problem for many poor countries the increasing rate of 
consumption in richer countries also is causing serious trouble 
this leads to the inescapable conclusion that we are eating 
into our capital assets to the detriment of future generations 
he said 
as the forests shrink as the marshes are drained as the 
rivers are polluted as the dams highways railroads factories 
and houses are built so the wildlife loses its habitat and unable 
to find any food and nowhere to breed it just dies out 
prince philip also stressed the need to control hunting and 
fishing to prevent the exploitation of animals 
there can be no doubt that such practices should come under 
some sort of international control but the perpetrators claim that 
the starving millions need the food and that they need the jobs 
he said 
it should not be very difficult to imagine the consequences of 
the indiscriminate exploitation of a dwindling resource in order to 
meet a rising demand 
