<TEXT>
organizations led by former labor secretary 
ray marshall asked a court on thursday to make president bush deny 
trade privileges to countries that violate their citizens labor 
rights 
the lawsuit was filed in the us district court for the 
district of columbia it did not name countries but a press 
statement said the organizations have documents to show violations 
in guatemala el salvador malaysia haiti the philippines 
thailand turkey and indonesia among others 
about 140 areas are privileged to ship some of their products to 
the united states dutyfree or at reduced duties under what is 
called the generalized system of preferences the reduced duties 
allow the products to be sold in this country at lower prices than 
similar goods from other countries the system is designed to help 
the third world countries develop their industries 
the law setting up the system limits the benefits to countries 
that respect internationally recognized worker rights these 
include a ban on child labor special provisions for women the 
right to form labor unions and others 
under this provision us authorities have banned nicaragua 
romania and burma from the program and suspended paraguay chile 
and the central african republic marshall and the other 
complainants consider that inadequate 
the bush administrations refusal to enforce the law gives 
large multinational firms a windfall at the expense of both 
american and foreign workers marshall said in a statement 
businesses can earn great profits in developing countries 
relatively free from labor regulation export their products 
dutyfree to the us market displace american workers and take 
advantage of unprotected foreign workers 
the complaint was filed by the aflcio and 22 other labor unions 
and private groups including marshalls own international labor 
rights education and research fund an advocacy group it asked the 
court to interpret the law and to order bush and his administration 
to review the rights of labor in all the countries that benefit 
from it 
the office of us trade representative carla hills said the 
action had been signalled in advance but it had no comment bush 
and six members of his cabinet named as defendants including ms 
hills have 60 days to reply 
