<TEXT>
at a small center with a single launch 
pad in the hills of uchinoura scientists are trying to make japan 
a leader in space 
private japanese companies count on them to succeed and have 
elaborate plans ranging from mines on the moon to a doughnutshaped 
orbiting hotel that would make its own gravity 
the government is known for targeting new technologies with 
wellfinanced research programs but uchinouras budget is small 
scientists stretch it by doing the work of technicians even 
checking the rockets 
staff members shiver during winter liftoffs because building 
heaters are shut down so the limited electrical supply can power 
the launch equipment 
despite years of trailing the united states and soviet union in 
both glamor and spending the japanese space industry has built a 
respected technical foundation and is aiming toward its own manned 
space program 
scientists at uchinouras institute of space and astronautical 
science put a satellite into lunar orbit march 19 using a small 
m3s2 rocket that made japan only the third nation to probe the 
moon 
japans other governmentfinanced space organization the 
national space development agency testfired a sophisticated 
engine march 7 for the h2 rocket which will compete with us 
soviet and european rockets in payload capacity 
so far japanese aerospace companies usually have been 
subcontractors for overseas firms or have manufactured products 
under foreign licenses 
in the past other nations took the initiative in space and 
japan participated passively but in the future japan will take the 
lead more often said tomifumi godai director of the space 
development agency 
as with many earlier industrial successes japan has avoided 
expensive space failures by licensing proven technology and 
gradually improving on it 
its the same old story says keisuke kasagi a senior 
analyst in tokyo for wi carr securities japan developed 
everything from foreign technology and then went on to develop its 
own domestic technology 
the workhorse h1 rocket uses 25yearold us delta technology 
developed by mcdonnell douglas with japanese improvements that 
include a new secondstage engine 
mcdonnell douglas recently asked mitsubishi heavy industries 
chief contractor on the h1 to supply it with the new engines for 
us rockets according to japanese space officials 
when i attend international meetings these days im often 
asked by other countries whether we will sell them technology 
godai told reporters 
an important gauge of that technology will be whether japan can 
complete development of the h2 rocket independently the engine 
caught fire in two tests last year delaying the first flight until 
at least march 1993 
having its own rockets would free japan from a 1969 agreement 
under which the united states can veto launching of satellites for 
third countries 
support for more independence may grow following discord over 
joint development plans with the united states for the fsx fighter 
plane discovery of design problems in a usled international 
space station project and the explosion feb 22 of a european 
ariane rocket carrying two japanese communications satellites worth 
about 600 million 
both satellites on the ariane were made in the united states 
american trade officials have threatened penalty tariffs on 
japanese products unless japan agrees to buy more us satellites 
instead of supporting development of the domestic satellite 
industry 
its hard to believe this great nation which produces so many 
goods so well has to protect an infant industry like satellites 
commerce secretary robert mosbacher said on a recent visit to japan 
some analysts question whether japan will become competitive in 
commercial launches 
its two small space centers at uchinoura and nearby 
tanegashima are far from the equator that increases launching 
costs for geostationary satellites which must be placed in orbits 
over the equator 
already there are wellestablished commercially viable launch 
programs in the united states europe the soviet union and 
china said stephen marvin an analyst for jardine fleming 
securities japan wont have the economies of scale to make it 
costeffective 
whatever the analysts say japanese space space plans are 
ambitious 
over the next 10 years the government program calls for 
creating a small space shuttle probes of the moon and venus to 
prepare for manned missions and building a 2 billion module for 
the space station 
most experiments in the module will involve processing materials 
in space as will many of the 34 experiments to be conducted by a 
japanese astronaut next year on the us space shuttle atlantis 
a group of 20 companies led by mitsubishi heavy industries plans 
to build a moon base by 2010 where humans can live for a few weeks 
by 2030 the group hopes to station more than 100 people there 
on a longterm basis to begin extracting helium3 as a source of 
power for nuclear fusion reactors which it said would mean no 
energy shortage on earth ever 
shimizu corp plans a doughnutshaped space hotel with 64 rooms 
that would orbit earth at an altitude of about 280 miles it would 
rotate three times a minute to create artificial gravity in the 
guest rooms and weightless space games could be played in the 
center of the ring 
japan is alloting 102 billion for space this year less than 
onetenth the 123 billion budgeted for the us national 
aeronautics and space administration 
analysts in the tokyo office of baring securities said spending 
probably would grow by 17 percent to 20 percent a year to an annual 
69 billion by the end of the decade 
</TEXT>
