<TEXT>
last winter ryuichi sakamoto turned on the tv 
in his los angeles hotel room and heard some familiar music 
fascinating he thought the orchestration the 
instrumentation how the french horns used high octave violin 
phrases 
it was the theme from bonanza 
im always looking for something which can inspire me said 
sakamoto who composed the academy awardwinning soundtrack to the 
the last emperor and has released a new album beauty 
when i listen to any music i automatically see musical notes 
and instruments in films just one tone a sound could mean a 
lot he said 
bonanza inspired sakamoto to purchase a compilation of 
themes from westerns which played softly in the background during 
a recent interview at a manhattan hotel he came to new york well 
prepared for any unexpected musical adventure on the dresser by 
his bed sat a compact disc player a digital audio tape machine and 
tapes of everything from reggae to jazz 
nicknamed professor in college sakamoto is like a sonic 
henry higgins able to tell the difference between hong kong and 
moscow by the pitch of car horns born in tokyo in 1952 he was 
just 10 when he began studying music composition at the university 
of art of tokyo 
but sakamoto is a proudly selftrained listener recalling his 
daily commutes to high school 
i paid attention to every noise on the train and counted every 
different noise spins boxes crashing people talking cable 
wires said sakamto who identified each sound with an uncanny 
imitation 
echoes of cities are different the first time i went to 
london i was kind of surprised i flew from tokyo to london and 
the echoes the cities had were very different said the composer 
whose debut album thousand knives was released in 1978 
in london the buildings were made out of stones the steps 
sounded very different to me very hypnotic 
sakamoto admits however that keeping his ears pinned to 
grindstone left him tonedeaf to people softspoken and shy he 
simply preferred listening to talking sounds over words the 
turning point he said came in 1987 when he worked with director 
bernardo bertolucci on the last emperor 
it was quite tricky because my musics kind of depressed and 
flat on the surface bertolucci forced me to write more and more 
emotional music he kept saying more emotional it was very 
difficult sakamoto said 
before the last emperor i was kind of afraid to let people 
into my music i could hardly communicate with people but after 
the experience of the last emperor i easily could communicate 
with people i was surprised 
so sakamoto calls beauty his most idealistic record a 
former loners attempt to embrace the world to the beat of world 
music the composers own mixture of dance rhythms and japanese 
folk 
each day i would say i need an african percussion player i 
need an african guitarist i need a korean guitar player i need a 
chinese musician i had so many different nusicians from all over 
the world and communication was so important for recording with 
them maybe three years ago i couldnt do that 
sakamoto has also worked with rock n rollers he appeared in 
the 1983 film merry christmas mr lawrence which starred 
david bowie and two years later collaborated with thomas dolby on 
the album field work 
on beauty he applies his personal touch to the rolling 
stones we love you the original was released in 1967 right 
after mick jagger and keith richards had been jailed briefly on 
drug charges with john lennon and paul mccartney singing backup 
the song was a cynical take on the summer of love complete with 
the sound of cell doors slamming 
but we love you was no joke to sakamoto who in 1967 was 
politically active and listening to the experimental music of john 
cage the composer got rid of the studio effects and turned the 
song into a friendly handshake offered of course via 
stateoftheart technology 
i wanted to have a song which was for people who i have never 
met he said i wanted to introduce myself to people who were 
not just music fans but all young people like ordinary people in 
the united states people in romania i want them to listen to my 
music 
</TEXT>
