<TEXT>
eight entreprenuers with a handmade 
transmitter satellite dish and broomcloset studio have broken the 
government monopoly on television broadcasts in what used to be the 
soviet bloc 
marek mlynarczyk smiled and said you might say weve made a 
little mess he is general manager of echotv the first private 
commercial television station in eastern europe 
echo has broadcast six hours a night since feb 6 mostly music 
videos and movies pirated more or less from satellite 
transmissions 
nobody believed we would do it said mlynarczyk who thinks 
thats the only reason he and his seven coowners got permission 
from the authorities 
they decided oh if you want permission just take it we 
dont believe you will do something with it he said the 
result is that now no other permissions are being given 
in decades of communist control polands two governmentrun 
television channels offered a dull diet of propaganda presented as 
news cheaptomake interview programs and cheaptobuy american 
reruns and brazilian soap operas occasionally a polish film 
spiced up the schedule 
poles are hooked on the tube nonetheless and mlynarczyk said 
the response to echotv was something of a shock at first 
there is no ratings system in poland but estimates put the 
number of viewers at 200000 for the station which can be picked 
up within about 18 miles of wroclaw an industrial city 200 miles 
southwest of warsaw 
some viewers need a special antenna demand was so great that 
stores sold out and the echotv office was mobbed when an 
advertising misprint implied the antennas were being sold there 
most people can receive echo without special equipment or set 
adjustments 
the station goes on the air at 6 pm from two tiny rooms atop a 
student dormitory where says one of the 16 staff technicians we 
could use a window 
virtually all the equipment fits on a table in one corner three 
televisions two video cassette recorders a personal computer and 
a special effects mixer 
another corner three steps away serves as the set for the 
fiveminute news program the footsquare logo backdrop is cut from 
paper 
andrzej zygmunt the technical manager cobbled together a 
transmitter slightly bigger than a bread box a cable strung 
through an air vent takes the signal to the roof 
the eight shareholders invested the equivalent of about 50000 
in what they call semiprofessional equipment to start the 
station and an affiliated video company 
so far they have more orders for oneminute computergenerated 
advertising messages than they can accommodate the rate is 5 per 
commercial 
were not dreaming of big money mlynarczyk said we just 
want to show we can maintain this 
this is the beginning we are making something new 
there are many plans afoot for original programming but for now 
most of the programs come from mtv the us music video channel 
and other stations carried by satellite 
