here are some statistics on the adirondack park 
at about 6 million acres the adirondack park is the largest 
public park in the lower 48 states it is 2 times the size of 
yellowstone national park about 23 million acres are a forest 
preserve protected under the state constitution as forever 
wild about 2 million acres are logged new york state owns about 
37 percent of the park 
lake placid in the heart of the park was the site of the 
winter olympics in 1932 and 1980 
the park is home to 130000 yearround residents there are 
110000 seasonal residents 
nine million people visit the park each year 
the park has 2000 miles of hiking trails and more than 100 
peaks at least 3000 feet high it encompasses more than 6000 
miles of streams and 2853 lakes and ponds more than 260 of its 
lakes are considered dead because of acid rain 
twohundredeighteen species of birds have been observed in the 
park along with 55 kinds of mammals 35 kinds of reptiles and 86 
varieties of fish 
the lynx peregrine falcon and bald eagle have been 
reintroduced to the adirondack park and officials may attempt to 
bring back the moose the park is the only area in the eastern 
united states being considered for reintroduction of the wolf and 
cougar 
</TEXT>
