<DOCNO> AP900330-0200 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the federal reserve board believes regulation 
of stocks and stock index futures by two separate government 
agencies has not worsened price swings in the stock markets 
chairman alan greenspan says 
greenspan told a senate panel thursday that while some fine 
tuning is in order the fed doesnt think creating one super 
regulator is the answer to jurisdictional disputes 
the board does not believe that the existing division of 
regulatory authority has increased volatility in the securities 
markets he said 
the head of the nations top economic policymaking body was 
among several key government officials to testify on the turf 
battle between the securities and exchange commission and the 
commodity futures trading commission 
greenspan told the securities subcommittee of the senate 
banking housing and urban affairs committee that he marginally 
favored giving jurisdiction over stock index futures to the sec 
but he quickly said he was speaking only for himself on that 
point and that several fed governors disagreed with that position 
the commodity futures trading commission oversees stock index 
futures which let investors bet on the rise and fall of a basket 
of stocks without having to buy the underlying securities 
but critics claim the wide disparity between margins the 
downpayment investors must make to buy securities on credit 
required in futures markets and the securities markets leads to 
sharp rises and drops in prices and that volatility they say has 
spooked small investors out of the stock market 
the federal reserve sets margin requirements for stocks and 
other securities but margins for futures contracts are set by the 
exchanges themselves usually at a fraction of the amount the fed 
requires 
greenspan said the fed does not see a clear basis for choosing 
between cftc and sec oversight of stock index futures margins 
he added however that the board feels strongly about 
giving up the margin authority it has already and putting the sec 
and the exchanges in charge of setting margins for stocks and stock 
options 
other witnesses included sec chairman richard c breeden cftc 
chairman wendy l gramm and treasury undersecretary robert r 
glauber 
while those three agencies have delivered opinions on who should 
regulate socalled hybrid financial products that contain 
aspects of both a security and a futures contract greenspan 
previously had kept mum 
last year a federal appeals court in chicago ruled that 
financial products with any properties of a futures contract belong 
under cftc oversight 
the fed treasury sec and cftc make up the presidents working 
group on financial markets a panel set up in the wake of the 1987 
stock market crash they have yet to reach an agreement on the 
thorny matter of jurisdiction for hybrid instruments like stock 
index futures 
breeden said he favored either merging control of securities and 
futures under one agency or at the least giving the sec control 
over stock index futures as well as stocks glauber said treasury 
favors giving the sec authority over stocks stock options and 
stock index futures 
gramm however opposes any shift in cftc jurisdiction 
claiming it hasnt been proven that such a change would benefit the 
markets 
the subcommittee chaired by sen christopher dodd dconn is 
looking specifically at the question of margins 
this hearing is not to debate the issue of turf dodd said 
at the hearings start but the topic quickly strayed to the 
longsimmering dispute between the sec and the cftc 
sen patrick leahy dvt chairman of the senate agriculture 
committee said the jurisdictional debate was holding up 
muchneeded reform in the commodities futures markets 
in testimony before dodds subcommittee he accused the sec of 
launching a hostile takeover of the cftcs responsibilities 
i am convinced that simply shifting jurisdiction for stock 
index futures from the cftc to the sec will not strengthen 
regulation end volatility in the stock market or restore investor 
confidence in wall street 
he called for passage of legislation to make the cftc a tougher 
regulator and then someday combine the cftc and sec 
but realistically the merger solution is far off said 
leahy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

