<DOCNO> AP900330-0201 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a chicago bank renowned for revitalizing its 
impoverished neighborhood is hoping to find a market for a novel 
instrument certificates of deposit for socially conscious 
investors 
for investors willing to forsake big yields the new cds from 
the south shore bank of chicago promise to give a boost to the 
citys south shore neighborhood and provide aid for groups such as 
vietnamese refugees bank officials said thursday 
i think its going to appeal to that universe of social 
investors who want to do something good with their money said 
katherine gross director of the revolving loan fund of the 
industrial cooperative association of somerville mass the banks 
partner in the effort 
a normal certificate of deposit might pay a 7 percent return 
but investors who buy a south shore cd can choose to keep 1 percent 
to 4 percent of the interest and give the rest to the ica 
a 100000 cd yielding 7 percent annually would return 7000 to 
an investor but if the south shore investor chose to earn only 1 
percent interest or 1000 the other 6000 in interest would be 
donated to the ica 
the nonprofit group invests such funds in locallyowned 
companies and community organizations around the country gross 
said prospective clients include an indian tribe in north dakota 
that wants to start a gas station and a group of vietnamese 
refugees who want to start a fishing cooperative she said 
the new cd serves a twofold purpose the interest goes to the 
nonprofit group while the principal is reinvested in the south 
shore neighborhood 
for someone who would like to promote social objectives this 
is a terrific investment said jan piercy vice president of 
shore bank corp the groups holding company but anyone who is 
interested in profit maximization is not going to be interested in 
this 
the bank has earned a national reputation for its efforts to 
revitalize the neighborhood 
like many other urban areas south shore suffered from the white 
flight to the suburbs the neighborhood went from nearly allwhite 
in the 1950s to 98 percent black by the early 1970s many banks and 
businesses fled during that time 
south shores previous owner even asked the federal reserve 
board for permission to move the bank to the loop chicagos 
downtown business district but the community revolted and the fed 
denied permission piercy said 
the owner decided to sell and a group of investors including 
several philanthropic foundations formed the holding company to 
buy the bank for 32 million in 1973 
the new owners decided to use the banks money to help the 
community and targeted socially conscious investors nationwide to 
increase its deposits 
during the last 15 years the bank has provided loans to 
renovate more than 22 percent of the neighborhoods rental units 
all of the funds which south shore gets from its depositors 
are targeted back into the community not into investments in junk 
bonds or oil said alan walker the banks administrator for 
development deposits 
that approach has won praise from some and the bank is the 
subject of a book called community capitalism by a university 
of chicago professor 
because of the banks efforts property values have steadily 
improved and the neighborhood is a better place to live than it 
was 10 or 15 years ago said dr richard taub a social science 
professor and author of the book 
