<TEXT>
kidder peabody group inc is selling its 
portfolio of risky junk bonds and bridge loans to its parents 
credit arm for about 750 million making it the latest wall street 
house to turn to its parent for capital 
analysts said the sale of the apparently illiquid investments to 
ge capital corp would increase kidders capital base and reduce 
its exposure to the dormant highyield bond market 
its going to make our balance sheet very much stronger and 
very much more liquid that it was prior to the deal kidder chief 
operating officer dick odonnell said 
the deal follows closely on the heels of efforts by american 
express co to bolster its ailing brokerage division in recent 
months american express has announced plans to take over shearson 
lehman hutton inc and inject about 135 billion in new capital 
kidder is a wholly owned subsidiary of general electric co 
it looks like were starting to see the beginning of a trend 
here said lawrence eckenfelder an industry analyst with 
prudentialbache securities inc it strengthens the balance sheet 
of these companies 
like other wall street firms kidder has been hurt by a downturn 
in the individual investing merger activity and securities 
underwriting the firm is shifting its retail operation to focus on 
wealthy clients and small companies rather than all investors 
kidder also has cut its work force to 5600 employees from a 
peak of 7500 
kidders 750 million portfolio is being sold at current market 
value but officials refused to reveal the face value of the 
investments 
the new york times reported that kidder would post an operating 
loss of less than 25 million for the first quarter to reflect the 
reduced value of the portfolio under the transaction 
about half the package is junk bonds and a third outstanding 
bridge loans credits made by kidder that were intended to be 
temporary but for which the firm failed to raise permanent 
financing the remaining onesixth is in equity investments in 
companies made by kidders merchant banking department 
kidder refused to say when the junk bonds were issued and bridge 
loans were made or to what companies 
it said three bridge loans had a total value of under 250 
million the bonds came from the firms merchant banking division 
and were not part of its daily trading portfolio 
odonnell said the firm was not getting out of the highyield 
bond business and would continue to maintain a trading inventory 
he also said kidder still would provide merchant banking 
services in which an investment firm takes an equity stake in its 
clients 
kidder officials sought to play down the comparison with 
shearson chairman and chief executive michael a carpenter said in 
a statement that ge capital is better positioned to realize the 
future value of the portfolio because it manages longerterm 
loans 
this is not a bailout whatsoever odonnell said they are 
buying 750 million worth of investments for cash this is an 
inventory which will be part of a much larger portfolio they 
manage 
he said the move will increase the net capital of kidders 
brokerdealer unit by about 100 million the value of its 
illiquid junk bond holdings that will push the regulated entitys 
capital to about 250 million above new york stock exchange 
requirements he said 
kidder lost 23 million last year compared with a 46 million 
profit in 1988 
ge the electrical products broadcasting and financial services 
company based in fairchild conn paid 600 million to acquire an 
80 percent stake in kidder in 1986 
