the government said friday it would wait five years 
before deciding whether to break up japans major 
telecommunications company whose recent stock slump has been 
linked in part to investor worries about a breakup 
the government still is the major shareholder in nippon 
telegraph and telephone corp which was converted into a private 
company in 1985 
for the time being we are going to promote rationalization of 
the company without breaking it up said minister of posts and 
telecommunications takashi fukaya and if it is deemed necessary 
to break up the company we will take up the matter again in 1995 
and make the final conclusion 
a government advisory council suggested earlier this month that 
ntt should be broken into three separate companies offering local 
longdistance and mobile telephone services 
after two years of study the council concluded that ntts 
virtual monopoly on telephone service has hindered free competition 
in japans telecommunications market and led to inefficient 
management of ntt 
a final government decision had been expected at the end of 
march when the government was required to review the state of the 
telecommunications market under the law that made ntt a private 
company five years ago 
but the finance ministry in charge of offering ntt stock to the 
public has strongly opposed a breakup claiming it will hurt ntt 
shareholders 
hundreds of shareholders have complained to the ministry that 
the price of ntt stock has slumped to about 11 million yen or 
7050 a share from 318 million yen or 20385 in april 1987 
shortly after its listing on the tokyo stock exchange 
company officials have attributed recent declines to a general 
stock market slump as well as worries about a breakup which ntt 
opposes on grounds it would lead to duplication of effort by the 
longdistance and local service companies 
finance minister ryutaro hashimoto said the governments 
decision to postpone a conclusion on breaking up ntt reflects the 
governments understanding about the concern of shareholders 
hashimoto also hinted that the ban on foreign investors holding 
ntt shares is likely to be removed soon 
