<TEXT>
the national association of securities dealers 
has proposed eliminating penny stocks from its overthecounter 
trading system partly in response to a crackdown on fraud in the 
lowcost securities 
the selfregulatory agency said thursday it would seek 
government approval to effectively double the standards companies 
must meet to be listed on the nasdaq stock system 
nasdaq stands for the national association of securities dealers 
automated quotations system a computerized stock price quotation 
system owned and operated by the nasd 
the move is expected to eliminate about 500 lowcost highrisk 
securities known as penny stocks because they usually trade for 
less than a dollar from the nasdaq system about 5000 stocks 
currently trade on nasdaq 
the new standards will not affect about 2700 stocks traded on 
the nasdaq national market which already has a higher standard 
the new standards adopted by the nasds board of governors 
earlier this month would require companies issuing stock for the 
first time to have a minimum of 4 million in total assets and 2 
million in capital and surplus compared to the present 
requirements of 2 million and 1 million 
in addition to the currently required 100000 shares of public 
float for an issue the float would have to have a market value of 
1 million float is the term used to describe the number of public 
shares circulating in the market 
stocks would have to have a minimum bid price of 3 per share 
there is no minimum required now 
maintaining a stock listing on nasdaq under the new rule would 
require a company to have 2 million in assets instead of the 
750000 in effect now also 1 million in capital surplus up 
from 375000 would be required the float would have to have a 
market value of 200000 and the stock would be required to have a 
1 minimum bid price 
the changes if approved by the securities and exchange 
commission would not go into effect until next january to give 
already listed companies time to meet the new rule 
nasd executive vice president john t wall said the changes 
reflected the effects of inflation since the requirements were last 
amended in 1981 
also prompting the changes was a jan 10 letter from the sec 
expressing concern that unscrupulous promoters might seek to 
circumvent tougher rules for selling penny stocks by acquiring a 
listing on nasdaq stock market 
such a listing would exempt them from the sec rule requiring a 
clients written consent to buy stocks not listed by nasdaq or a 
stock exchange 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

