<DOCNO> AP900330-0227 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
political and economic trends have overtaken 
japans financial markets painfully ending an era during which 
investing in the tokyo stock exchange seemed to be a sure thing 
analysts say 
from the beginning of 1990 through fridays close of trading 
the market that once was the worlds richest had lost 23 percent of 
its value 
the japanese yen also has weakened dropping more than 9 percent 
to about 158 yen to the us dollar after ending last year at 
14345 yen and the dollars rise to a threeyear high against the 
yen has occurred despite heavy dollarselling by japans central 
bank 
market analysts say these trends could continue during the next 
few months as the yen and inflated stock prices readjust to 
political developments and economic realities that have overtaken 
japans monetary authorities and major brokerages 
japans big four securities firms nomura securities daiwa 
securities nikko securities and yamaichi account for about half 
of the tokyo markets total turnover 
their market activity and advice often are credited with pulling 
the market out of slumps such as the oct 20 1987 crash that 
followed the black monday plunge on wall street and with 
instilling the confidence that pushed the key nikkei average up 
almost 20000 points between early 1987 and the end of last year 
when it peaked at 3891587 
theres little doubt the major brokers accounted for lots of 
the market activity in the latter half of last year when the 
market surged by about 4000 points says economist david pike at 
ubs phillips and drew international ltd 
but the late 1989 surge contradicted economic fundamentals by 
reacting to speculation that interest rates were peaking he said 
rather than peaking domestic interest rates have continued 
rising as monetary authorities fight inflationary pressures 
stemming from wage hikes a 3 percent sales tax and the weaker yen 
which raises the cost of fuel and other imports 
japans central bank has raised its discount rate the interest 
it charges on loans to commercial banks four times since last may 
to fight inflation which economists expect to be in the 2 
percent25 percent range this year 
the discount rate which has a strong impact on other interest 
rates was raised to 525 percent on march 20 it was at a historic 
low of 25 percent before the series of increases 
higher interest rates tend to discourage investment in the stock 
market because higher yields can be found in other investments 
analysts see higher rates as the single biggest factor behind the 
stock markets prolonged decline 
the yens decline also has pushed stock prices lower 
higher interest rates generally make a countrys currency more 
attractive to investors by reducing the outflow of capital from 
japan in the long run the discount rate hike could reduce demand 
for dollars and relieve downward selling pressure on the yen 
but the bank of japan was backed into a corner because 
boosting rates was certain to further hurt the stock market says 
peter morgan chief economist at barclays de zoete wedd securities 
japan ltd 
moreover currency dealers had anticipated the latest rate 
increase which so far has failed to help in fact the dollar by 
late friday had risen to 15765 yen from 15270 yen on march 20 
the yen also has suffered due to political developments in the 
soviet union and eastern europe which have strengthened the us 
dollar seen as safest in times of uncertainty 
furthermore western europe has become sexy due to 
expectations of german reunification and the formation of the 
european common market in 1992 luring japanese investors away from 
home markets morgan said 
many analysts say they expect the market to continue declining 
in the short term as it adjusts to factors beyond the control of 
brokerages or monetary authorities 
market sentiment is still deteriorating so we certainly cant 
expect a sharp recovery says susumu kato senior economist at 
goldman sachs japan 
this year higher borrowing costs will depress capital 
investment and the weaker yen will increase the cost of imports 
cutting into corporate earnings says lawrence s prager chief 
analyst and strategist at nikko securities co 
but in the long run japans powerhouse economy will take the 
adjustments in stride analysts say 
these are not caused by major economic problems but are a 
matter of sentiment says kermit l schoenholtz senior economist 
at salomon brothers asia ltd the economy is extraordinarily 
competitive and the weaker yen will further boost its export 
competitiveness 
</TEXT>
