on 315 million owed to banks and increases the availability of 
funds to univision 
hallmark also said it had agreed with the banks that if the 
restructuring of univisions debt is completed hallmark will defer 
interest payments on the securities tendered for seven years rather 
than the five years earlier proposed 
company executives say that while univisions business is 
growing the company has run into stiffer than expected competition 
and has been unable to meet the terms of its current financial 
structure 
univision missed 10 million in interest payments that were due 
feb 1 to its bank lenders and bondholders citing insufficient 
cash flow 
several days later hallmark launched a plan to rescue univision 
that included paying 10575 million for its 270 million in bond 
debt 
but hallmark said that with one day left under its onceextended 
tender offers that were to have expired at 1201 am friday only 
8 percent of one issue and 4 percent of the other had been 
tendered hallmark wanted at least 95 percent of the bonds tendered 
under the initial offers 
the revised tender offers are scheduled to expire at 1201 am 
friday april 13 and hallmark lowered the minimum acceptable 
amount to 90 percent 
hallmark paid about 600 million to acquire the univision 
network and tv stations over three years ended in 1988 it owns a 
635 percent stake in univision while first chicago investment 
corp holds 215 percent and a private trust owns the remainder 
wilbur ross senior managing director at rothschild inc which 
is serving as financial advisor to holders of a majority of the 
univision bonds said the first hallmark offer had been pretty 
much rejected out of hand 
but he said the new offers which hallmark valued at 131 
million were about 25 percent higher than the first ones valued at 
106 million 
we regard this as a very constructive development it is a 
good faith offer no decision has yet been made but people are 
taking this offer quite seriously ross said 
among the issues which will be studied he said are the 
sufficiency of the offers and how they allocate values between the 
two debt issues 
