<TEXT>
the perjury conviction of former drexel burnham 
lambert inc trading assistant lisa jones was upheld friday by a 
federal appeals court but her 18month jail sentence was thrown 
out 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals ruled the trial judge 
wrongly gave her a sentence greater than the 10 to 16month term 
recommended by new sentencing guidelines the case was sent back to 
us district judge leonard b sand for resentencing 
the threejudge panel said sands reason for lengthening the 
sentence that jones perjury severely impeded the governments 
drexel investigation was not justified 
a federal jury in march 1989 found jones guilty on five counts 
of perjury and two counts of obstruction of justice for lying to a 
federal grand jury in january 1988 in an investigation of trading 
involving drexel 
these instances of perjury standing alone do not constitute 
the type of egregious conduct envisioned by the guidelines as 
substantial interference with the administration of justice the 
24page appeals court opinion said 
jones who left home at age 14 climbed to a 100000ayear job 
as an assistant bond trader in drexels highyield junk bond 
department in beverly hills calif formerly run by nowindicted 
executive michael milken 
in three appearances before the federal grand jury jones said 
she did not recall any discussions about stock parking in 
contacts with princetonnewport partners lp a defunct investment 
firm whose principals were convicted of securities fraud in july 
parking refers to placing stock temporarily with another party 
to hide its true ownership the practice is illegal when it is used 
to circumvent regulations that require stockholders to disclose 
shares they own in companies 
the appeals court upheld her conviction by ruling against three 
issues raised by her lawyer in the appeal that jones was denied 
effective counsel by her trial attorney that the prosecutor 
conducted an improper crossexamination when she testified at 
trial and that the judge made an incomplete examination of a juror 
whose son was a federal prosecutor in new jersey 
jones attorney daniel bookin said he had not decided whether 
to appeal her conviction further he would not comment on the 
appeals court decision 
her resentencing was not yet scheduled 
