<TEXT>
federal reserve policy makers decided at their 
february meeting to continue their high interest rate policies to 
keep inflationary pressures under control according to minutes 
released friday 
the federal funds rate has remained steady at 825 percent since 
the fed permitted it to drop from 85 percent on dec 21 following 
the previous fed policy meeting on dec 1819 
the federal funds rate is the interest banks charge each other 
for overnight loans and is the primary lever the fed uses to 
control shortterm interest rates 
the policymaking body the federal open market committee met 
again tuesday and analysts believe it voted to continue current 
policies minutes of that meeting will not be released until may 
the committee holds closed meetings eight times a year to 
formulate monetary policy and confers by telephone as needed it 
consists of the seven federal reserve board members and five of the 
12 presidents of the fed district banks 
at the fomc meeting feb 67 the information on economic 
conditions suggested continued but sluggish expansion in 
overall economic activity with conditions uneven across sectors 
the minutes read 
industrial activity remained weak partly because of the 
depressing effects of an inventory correction on manufacturing 
output while the serviceproducing sector of the economy continued 
to grow moderately they continued 
the minutes stated that prices increased more slowly over most 
of the second half of 1989 but unusually cold wather in december 
put temporary upward pressure on food and energy prices 
and they added the staff projection prepared for this 
meeting suggested that the economy was likely to expand relatively 
slowly over the next several quarters 
but while the policymakers generally agreed that continuing 
growth in economic activity remained a reasonable expectation for 
the year ahead the minutes said members acknowledged that 
there were considerable risks and some did not rule out the 
possibility of a downturn 
at the conclusion of the meeting the fomc voted 83 not to 
change policies although they agreed some firming or easing of 
credit would be acceptable depending on economic developments 
 
