<DOCNO> AP900330-0250 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a top gaf corp executive was sentenced friday 
to six months in prison and the company was fined 2 million for 
stock manipulation convictions stemming from the governments 
crackdown on wall street crime 
us district judge mary johnson lowe said she ordered a prison 
term for gaf vice chairman james t sherwin because his conviction 
should be used as a lesson to others who may be tempted to engage 
in conduct such as this 
sherwin 56 and gaf were convicted in december on eight counts 
of stock manipulation securities fraud conspiracy and 
recordkeeping violations in a scheme to boost the stock price of 
union carbide corp after a failed takeover 
gaf a wayne nj speciality chemicals concern was the first 
company outside of wall street to be convicted in the governments 
insider trading investigation that began in 1986 the gaf case was 
based on information indirectly supplied by convicted arbitrager 
ivan boesky 
i do not believe that a sentence should be imposed upon you to 
punish you as a person lowe told sherwin i do this with 
heavy heart because i believe you are a good man 
but the judge said she felt compelled to issue prison time to 
send a message to wall street that if financial market participants 
break the law there will be a prison sentence at the end of the 
road 
gaf attorney arthur liman said an appeal was planned sherwin 
remains free pending appeal under the sentence liman said 
sherwin would have to serve five months in prison with one month 
off for good behavior 
sherwin who once was the nations thirdranked chess player 
slumped in his chair as the verdict was read he declined to 
comment afterward and was embraced by his tearful wife two of his 
three daughters and three stepdaughters 
the case attracted wide attention on wall street when gaf two 
subsidiaries and sherwin were indicted in july 1988 for allegedly 
trying to inflate the price of union carbide stock in 1986 the 
illegal action allegedly occurred shortly before gaf sold a large 
block of union carbide shares it acquired in an unsuccessful 
takeover attempt 
the case endured two mistrials the first in early 1989 after 
the government inadvertently withheld a key piece of evidence and 
the second after a jury was unable to reach a verdict after 12 days 
of deliberations 
gaf a chemicals and building parts manufacturer faced a 
maximum fine of 4 million sherwin faced a maximum five years in 
prison and 250000 fine on each count 
the parties recently paid 125 million to settle a civil 
lawsuit with the securities and exchange commission on similar 
allegations as in the criminal case 
judge lowe sentenced sherwin to six months in prison on one 
count each of stock manipulation and recordkeeping violations she 
suspended sentence on the other six counts and placed sherwin on 
one year probation 
the government did not recommend a prison term for sherwin 
saying only that a substantial sentence was warranted 
the manipulation was done purely out of greed and not out of 
financial necessity the government said in its sentencing 
memorandum in short the scheme was calculated and 
wellplanned 
sherwin his voice cracking told lowe any sentence the judge 
deems appropriate i am prepared to accept 
stephen kaufman sherwins attorney asked lowe to order only 
community service he said sherwin has a stellar reputation in 
business is active in human rights causes and was not a 
systemic violator 
this was an aberrational act an isolated act an act totally 
out of character with anything hes done in his life kaufman 
said 
lowe said she could not recall a case in her 18 years as a judge 
that had caused me more anguish in attempting to fashion an 
appropriate sentence 
prosecutors based their case on testimony of former los angeles 
stockbroker boyd l jefferies he testified that sherwin directed 
him to buy large blocks of union carbide in late 1986 in an attempt 
to raise its price to 22 a share and agreed to pay 40000 to 
cover his losses 
a higher stock price would have meant more money for gaf which 
had accumulated 10 million shares of union carbide during the 
failed takeover bid that year gaf later sold 5 million shares to 
salomon brothers inc for 23 a share 
jefferies also played a key role in two other securities fraud 
convictions last year of florida investor paul a bilzerian and 
arbitrager salim b lewis bilzerian was sentenced to prison while 
jefferies and lewis were fined and ordered to perform community 
service 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

