under pressure from their government to support the yen may not 
buy as many treasury bonds as they would otherwise over the next 
few months 
some traders stayed out of the market while they await a pair of 
important economic reports next week the latest monthly survey by 
the national association of purchasing management and the march 
unemployment figures 
the purchasing management association of chicago reported friday 
that its index of area business activity rose to 551 percent in 
march from 51 percent in february it was the highest reading since 
april 
a reading above 50 indicates expansion in the manufacturing 
sector and a reading below 50 indicates contraction 
the chicago index is based on a survey of company purchasing 
managers in northern illinois and northwestern indiana one of the 
largest industrial areas in the country it was viewed as an 
indication that nationwide business conditions may show improvement 
as well 
evidence of a revival in the economy would be hurt the bond 
market because it would reinforce the belief that the federal 
reserve might be leaning toward tightening its credit policy by 
nudging up interest rates bond prices recede when interest rates 
rise 
