<TEXT>
btr plc of britain sought a federal injunction 
friday to keep norton co from delaying a shareholder proxy fight 
after norton rejected a 16 billion buyout bid 
the request was contained in a lawsuit that also challenges 
massachusetts antitakeover law and nortons poison pill 
defense against hostile bidders norton countersued friday seeking 
to halt btrs tender offer and proxy solicitation 
btr a londonbased industrial conglomerate announced its 
75pershare bid earlier this month for norton a leading 
manufacturer of abrasives 
on thursday worcesterbased norton turned down the offer 
calling it inadequate its board of directors said it was 
canceling the companys annual meeting scheduled for april 26 and 
set a special shareholders meeting for june 26 
the board said it needed more time to explore its options 
including the possibility of attracting a minority investor to help 
thwart the bid 
but btrs complaint filed in us district court in boston 
said nortons bylaws prohibit the annual meeting from being 
rescheduled within 60 days of the date set for the meeting 
the british firm said it was prepared to enter a proxy fight at 
the annual meeting to elect its own slate of directors to the 
company 
the change in the meeting date will destroy the opportunity 
for the norton shareholders to hear the platform of the btr 
nominees the complaint said 
norton in its lawsuit accused btr of making false and 
misleading public statements about its plans for the company 
btr intentionally has tried to obfuscate the critical facts 
concerning its past acquisitions and employment practices in which 
the company has repeatedly closed or relocated plants fired 
large numbers of employees and retaliated against organized labor 
and attempts by workers to organize 
btrs lawsuit claimed massachusetts antitakeover law is 
unconstitutional judith fabricant an assistant attorney general 
said the complaint essentially is moot because the state has not 
enforced the statute since a federal court raised questions about 
its validity in 1988 
we do not intend to enforce it she said but we are not 
taking a position to whether it is valid or not valid 
the lawsuit seeks an injunction against nortons poison pill 
plan which would boost the cost of a takeover unless the board of 
directors consents to the offer btr claims the plan breaches the 
companys duty to stockholders 
the state however has challenged btrs claims saying nortons 
responsibility is not limited to its shareholders 
under massachusetts law a company targeted for a takeover also 
may consider the impact on employees customers suppliers the 
community and the state economy fabricant said 
