<TEXT>
franklin savings association and the office 
of thrift supervision reached agreement friday on the issue of 
receivership after an almost twohour negotiating session among 
lawyers in federal court 
the agreement essentially gives franklin a chance to argue its 
case in court if the os decides to put the states largest thrift 
into receivership a receiver could liquidate all of franklins 
assets 
franklin and its holding company franklin savings corp 
withdrew their motion for a preliminary injunction against ots and 
the kansas savings and loan department in us district court the 
injunction was designed to prevent appointment of a receiver until 
franklin has its day in court to contest the resolution trust 
corps conservatorship of the thrift 
the agreement outlined to judge dale saffels provides that no 
receiver will be appointed or substituted for the present 
conservator without giving notice to the court and to franklin 24 
hours in advance the agreement also requires the thrift office to 
justify to the court its reason for appointing a receiver if it 
attempts to do so 
earlier the ots only agreed to give franklin the advance notice 
franklin which was seized by the rtc on feb 16 believed the 
rtcs conservatorship was merely a prelude to a receivership once 
a receiver is appointed the court cant intervene 
the thrift said it will contest the validity of the 
conservatorship in a trial set to begin june 25 in saffels court 
here 
attorneys for franklin came prepared with exhibits to argue 
their case attorneys for ots said they also were prepared 
saffels however asked both parties to try to come to an agreement 
the negotiating session involved a call to washington dc to 
secure approval of the compromise by ots officials 
ots attorney paul w grace of washington said normally no notice 
is required for appointment of a receiver he would not say whether 
he was pleased or displeased with the agreement 
lets just say its a compromise both sides are willing to 
accept grace said 
ernest fleischer chairman of franklins holding company and on 
leave as chairman of the thrift said he was pleased with the 
agreement an attorney for franklin charles german said of the 
agreement its what we came for 
the justice department was present at the hearing to argue the 
constitutionality of the appointment of former ots director m 
danny wall who authorized franklins conservatorship however 
saffels said he was not willing to take up that issue which arose 
when a federal district judge in washington ruled last week that 
walls appointment was unconstitutional an appeals court later 
stayed that ruling pending its review of it 
franklin contends the thrift was not insolvent at the time it 
was taken over by federal regulators the thrift and the ots differ 
over the accounting principles used by franklin 
franklin through the president of its holding company john 
scowcroft claims it has a net worth of 387 million using 
generally accepted accounting principles 
the ots agrees with that figure but only as of dec 31 1989 
said spokeswoman cindy williams she said that figure likely would 
be down by next quarters report but could not release a monthly 
figure the thrift experienced a major writedown in its capital in 
march 
the thrift was hedging itself against swings in interest rates 
by using the futures market 
</TEXT>
