<TEXT>
coloradoute electric association 
losing a yearlong battle against financial disaster filed in us 
bankruptcy court in denver on friday for protection from creditors 
while it attempts to salvage itself 
the case is one of the largest utility bankruptcy filings in the 
country according to federal officials and threatens the 
longterm cost of power for consumers in much of colorado 
with 12 billion in debt coloradoute filed for chapter 11 
reorganization to stave off its many creditors while it tries to 
solve its problems 
coloradoute based in montrose in western colorado is owned by 
14 member rural electric coops and serves an estimated 600000 
customers 
the filing will have no effect on daytoday operations of the 
utility president ray keith said in a news release 
on march 31 1989 coloradoute defaulted on its loans blaming 
the oil shale bust for leaving the company with excess capacity 
however the bust was triggered by exxon corps pullout from the 
industry in 1982 and coloradoute not only pushed ahead with plant 
construction but also launched an expensive experimental power 
plant at nucla that still loses money 
coloradoute lost an estimated 15 million in 1989 
in its filing coloradoute listed liabilities of 9202 million 
and assets of 8883 million the documents do not reflect the 
companys 300 million lease obligation on its craig 3 power plant 
the company says the lease obligation is not a debt 
most of the liabilities are held by two federal lenders the 
us rural electrification administration and the national 
consolidated finance corp for a combined debt of more than 700 
million to the federal government 
other major creditors listed on the court filing were 
public service co of colorado 314 million of debt 
colowyo coal co 236 million for disputed coal royalties 
craig 3 lease trustee 118 million in current lease payments 
norwest bank of minneapolis united bank of denver and 
manufacturers hanover trust 10 million each 
in the year since coloradoute defaulted the company tried to 
merger with both public service co of colorado and tristate 
generation amp transmission co it also attempted to raise rates by 
237 percent 
public service co withdrew its offer last summer on march 8 
state regulators denied the big rate increase allowing only an 8 
percent hike tristate like coloradoute a generating company 
owned by its rural coops halted merger talks after the rate hike 
denial and then cut off coloradoutes access to a 40 million 
revolving loan 
with no access to cash and facing a monday deadline for a 15 
million interest payment to the rea the utility filed in 
bankruptcy court late friday afternoon 
